SIMPLE: intemperance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intemperance
<hw>In*tem"per*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>intemp⟦eacute⟧rance</ets>, L. <ets>intemperantia</ets>. See
<er>In-</er> not, and <er>Temperance</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of becoming, or state of being, intemperate;
excess in any kind of action or indulgence; any immoderate indulgence of
the appetites or passions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God is in every creature; be cruel toward none, neither abuse any
by <qex>intemperance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some, as thou sawest, by violent stroke shall die,⟦br⟧
By fire, flood, famine, by <qex>intemperance</qex> more⟦br⟧
In meats and drinks.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>Habitual or excessive
indulgence in alcoholic liquors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intemperancy</ent>⟦br⟧
